{{Merge|Francisco Mendigaño Armendáriz|date=September 2018}} {{Spanish name|Mendigaña|Armendáriz}}{{Infobox Christian leader | honorific-prefix = [[The Most Reverend]] | name = Francisco Mendigaña y Armendáriz | title = Archbishop of Santo Domingo | church = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic Church]] | archdiocese = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santo Domingo|Santo Domingo]] | appointed = 8 April 1726 | term_end = 30 October 1728 | predecessor = [[Antonio Claudio Alvarez de Quiñones]] | successor = [[Juan de Galavís]], [[Norbertines|O. Praem]] | birth_date = 17 May 1674 | birth_place = [[Astráin]], [[Navarre]], [[Spain]] | death_date = 30 October 1728 (aged 54) | death_place = [[Machetá]], [[Viceroyalty of New Granada]] }}
'''Francisco Mendigaña y Armendáriz''' (17 May 1674 – 30 October 1728) was a [[Spain|Spanish]]-born [[prelate]] of the [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic Church]]. Born in [[Navarre]], he moved to [[Viceroyalty of New Granada|New Granada]] as an adult, serving in leadership positions in the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bogotá|Archdiocese of Bogotá]]. Following Archbishop [[Francisco del Rincón]]'s death in 1723, he became the diocesan administrator of the archdiocese, and was appointed [[Archbishop of Santo Domingo]] in April 1726. He remained in Bogotá until 1727 or 1728, when he left for his new position in Santo Domingo, but he died along the way in 1728.
== Biography ==
=== Early life and education === Mendigaña y Armendáriz was born on 17 May 1674 in the village of [[Astráin]], [[Navarre]], [[Spain]].<ref name=":4">{{Cite web|url=http://catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bmendig.html|title=Archbishop Francisco Mendigaño Armendáriz [Catholic-Hierarchy]|last=Cheney|first=David M.|website=catholic-hierarchy.org|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref><ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=https://www.geni.com/people/Francisco-Mendiga%C3%B1a-y-Armend%C3%A1riz-Arzobispo-de-Santo-Domingo/6000000020269820913|title=Francisco Mendigaña y Armendáriz, Arzobispo de Santo Domingo|website=geni_family_tree|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref><ref name=":6">{{Cite news|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/zdom0.htm|title=Archdiocese of Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic|newspaper=GCatholic|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref> His parents were Juan Mendigaña and Graciosa Armendáriz, and he had one sister, María Catharina.<ref name=":5" /><ref name=":7">{{Cite journal|last=Tisnés|first=Roberto María|year=1958|title=Mendigaña: Ulitmos años y actuaciones de un arzobispo de Santo Domingo ... que no lo fue|url=http://clio.academiahistoria.org.do/trabajos/clio113/Clio_1958_No_113-09.pdf|journal=Clio|volume=113|pages=101–121|via=}}</ref> For secondary school, he attended the [[Colegio Mayor de San Ildefonso]] in [[Alcalá de Henares]], Spain.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Casado Arboniés|first=Manuel|year=1998|title=Dos arzobispados americanos para el estudiante de Alcalá Don Antonio Claudio Álvarez de Quiñones|url=http://dspace.uah.es/dspace/bitstream/handle/10017/6170/Dos%20Arzobispados%20Americanos%20para%20el%20Estudiante%20de%20Alcal%C3%A1%20Don%20Antonio%20Claudio%20%C3%81lvarez%20de%20Qui%C3%B1ones%201712-1736.pdf?sequence=1|journal=Estudios de historia social y económica de América|volume=|pages=268–283|issn=0214-2236|via=}}</ref> In his youth, he once traveled to the [[Viceroyalty of New Granada]], but returned to Spain.<ref name=":7" />
=== Priesthood and episcopacy === Mendigaña returned to New Granada as an adult, this time permanently.<ref name=":7" /> He settled in [[Bogotá]] where he spent much of his priestly career, serving in the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bogotá|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santafé en Nueva Granada]] (now the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bogotá|Archdiocese of Bogotá]]). By 1717, at the time of the death of Archbishop [[Francisco Otero y Cossío]], Mendigaña was serving as [[treasurer]] of the archdiocese.<ref name=":7" />
On 28 June 1723, Archbishop [[Francisco del Rincón]], died of illness.<ref name=":7" /><ref name=":0" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite journal|last=|first=|year=|title=Familias Hispanoamericanas|url=http://bagn.academiahistoria.org.do/boletines/boletin99-100/BAGN_1959_No_99-100-04.pdf|journal=Boletin del Archivo General de la Nacion|volume=|pages=44–56|via=}}</ref> [[Antonio Claudio Álvarez de Quiñones]] was appointed Archbishop of Santafé en Nueva Granada on 29 January 1725 in a [[papal bull]] by [[Pope Benedict XIII]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":3" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/balqu.html|title=Archbishop Antonio Claudio Alvarez de Quiñones [Catholic-Hierarchy]|last=Cheney|first=David M.|website=www.catholic-hierarchy.org|access-date=2017-02-19}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/zdom0.htm|title=Archdiocese of Santo Domingo, Dominican Republic|newspaper=GCatholic|access-date=2017-02-19}}</ref> However, he did actually take reach the archdiocese until 1731, due to an extended illness and travels to Europe.<ref name=":7" /><ref name=":0" /><ref name=":3" /> Following Rincón's death, Mendigaña, who had been previously the archdeacon, became [[diocesan administrator]] of the archdiocese.<ref name=":7" /><ref name=":0" />
On 8 April 1726, Mendigaña was appointed Archbishop of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santo Domingo|Santo Domingo]] by [[Pope Benedict XIII]].<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":7" /> He remained in Bogotá in the meanwhile, continuing to serve as diocesan administrator while he awaited Álvarez de Quiñones' arrival so that he could [[Episcopal consecration|consecrate]] him as bishop before he left for Santo Domingo.<ref name=":0" /> However, when Álvarez de Quiñones did not arrive, in 1727 or 1728 Mendigaña departed Bogotá for Santo Domingo, around two years after being appointed archbishop.<ref name=":7" /> His successor as diocesan administrator was Nicolás de Barasorda y Larrazabal.<ref name=":7" /><ref name=":0" /> Meanwhile, while traveling to Santo Domingo, Mendigaña died along the way, on 30 October 1728<ref name=":4" /><ref name=":5" /><ref name=":6" /> in the town of [[Machetá]] in what is now [[Colombia]].<ref name=":7" />
