{{Infobox Election | election_name = House of Representatives election, 1984 | country = South Africa | flag_year = 1982 | type = parliamentary | ongoing = no | previous_election = South African general election, 1981 | previous_year = 1981 | previous_mps = | next_election = South African general election, 1987 | next_year = 1987 | next_mps = | seats_for_election = All 80 elected seats in the [[House of Representatives of South Africa|House of Representatives]] | election_date = 22 August 1984 <!-- Labour Party (South Africa, 1969) --> | image1 = | leader1 = [[Allan Hendrickse]] | color1 =8B0000 | leader_since1 = | party1 = Labour Party (South Africa, 1969) | leaders_seat1 = | seats1 = 76 | map_image = South African House of Representatives 1984.svg | map_size = 300px | map_caption = House of Representatives after the election }}
{{Infobox Election | election_name = House of Delegates election, 1984 | country = South Africa | flag_year = 1982 | type = parliamentary | ongoing = no | previous_election = South African general election, 1981 | previous_year = 1981 | previous_mps = | next_election = South African general election, 1987 | next_year = 1987 | next_mps = | seats_for_election = All 40 elected seats in the [[House of Delegates of South Africa|House of Delegates]] | election_date = 28 August 1984
<!-- Minority Front --> | image1 = | leader1 = [[Amichand Rajbansi]] | color1 = DC143C | party1 = National People's Party (South Africa, 1981) | seats1 = 18
| image2 = | leader2 = [[JN Reddy]] | color2 = FF0000 | party2 = Solidarity (South African political party) | seats2 = 17 | map_image = [[File:House of Delegates 1984.png]] | map_size = 300px | map_caption = House of Delegates after the election }} {{Politics of South Africa}} '''General elections''' were held in [[South Africa]] in August 1984 to elect [[Coloured]] and [[Asians in South Africa|Indian]] representatives to their respective houses of the [[Tricameral Parliament]]. The Coloured elections for the [[House of Representatives of South Africa|House of Representatives]] took place on 22 August, and resulted in a victory for the [[Labour Party (South Africa, 1969)|Labour Party]], headed by the [[Reverend]] [[Allan Hendrickse]], which won 76 of the 80 seats. The Indian elections for the [[House of Delegates of South Africa|House of Delegates]] were held on 28 August and saw the [[National People's Party (South Africa, 1981)|National People's Party]] emerge as the largest party, winning 18 of the 40 seats.<ref name=AED>[http://africanelections.tripod.com/za.html#1984_House_of_Delegates_Election Elections in South Africa] African Elections Database</ref> The Indian elections were opposed by the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] and were marked by boycotts and protests.<ref name=AED/>
==Background== In addition to the whites-only [[House of Assembly of South Africa|House of Assembly]], a November 1983 referendum had approved the creation of two new houses an 80-member [[House of Representatives (South Africa)|House of Representatives]] for Coloureds and a 40-member [[House of Delegates (South Africa)|House of Delegates]] for Asians.
